def: One who writes tracts; specif., a Tractarian. [R.] C. Kingsley.

A disagreement or difference between two parts of the samelegal proceeding, which, to be effectual, ought to agree, -- asbetween the writ and the declaration, or between the allegation andthe proof. Bouvier. A variance, in disagreement; in a state ofdissension or controversy; at enmity. "What cause brought him so soonat variance with himself" Milton.
A thick woolen stuff quilled or twilled.
One of the fossil Conifer√¶, evidently allied to the juniper.
Of the color of a peach blossom. "Peach-colored satin." Shak.
A little quarrel. See 1st Quarrel, 2. [Obs.] "Quarrelets ofpearl [teeth]." Herrick.
Having or celebrating a triumph; victorious; triumphant.-- Tri"umph*ing*ly, adv.
A sort of bar or movable nut, attached to the finger board of aguitar or other  fretted instrument for the purpose of raisinguniformly the pitch of all the strings.
State of being acquainted; degree of acquaintance. [R.] Boyle.
